<font style="font-size:10"><A href="http://www.andreasen.org/bartle/test.cgi">Explorer-66% Killer-60% Socializer-46% Achiever-26%</A></font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEEFDE><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/uutnayan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Utnayan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Eventempered<br>Retired MMDN Admin</span><br>  Posts: 1071<br> <font color=#006400>(1/15/02 5:01:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=991.topic&index=4>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: This Just in! RVR POINTS MEAN SOMETHING in DAOC!</span><hr size=1> Let the customers try and address a game and you have DAOC. <br>
<br>
People bitched about twinking, rare items, rare spawns, but now those same people in DAOC are bitching that the game has no economy. <br>
<br>
People bitched about crafting systems. Well now they have a new one, it is designed decently but a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> tremendous</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> timesink. Not too sure what levels you have attained, but after 400 in tailoring, the time it took to create a new item was over a minute. Just sitting there not moving. The task system for crafting I will admit is nice. Makes it so if you just want to craft and never play the game in a PVP PVE sense, you can. But than again, no one buys your items. Sorry Flint past 39 there are no decent items that a crafter can make comparable to droppable items. In which case you are camping the same type of mob to get that rare drop. Pick joutons for the clay weapon drops in swamp in Midgard. Killing ther same stupid mob over and over again. How is this different? Except now your heart does not race when you see a special named monster. <br>
<br>
People bitched about power leveling. Looks like they took care of that with their group experience fix. <br>
<br>
Why do people still play Everquest? Because there is still a lot of stuff to do. I thought the same as you do Flint.  I thought hell as high water that when something else came out Everquest would be history. What I am finding out is the more people listen to the players of Everquest bitch than conform a game to it, the more I love Everquest for what it really is. <br>
<br>
Sure the timesinks are incredible. But at least the game has a perceived value to the items in the game. I still get excited when I get a new piece of armor or a new weapon in EQ now.  When I see a named spawn I am always curious to see what it drops. In DAOC I trained myself to just consider it just another mob. <br>
<br>
Story?  I have seen no history, books, anything in game you can read about the storyline behind any of the dungeons in Midgard, or the areas in which places are located and how they came to be. I think they need a creative writer for this. For instance a farm over in the back of Fort Atla maybe could have been over run by an evil force causing all the pigs to go rabid, and having an NPC in the area to tell the story. All of this is missing from DAOC. <br>
<br>
Just the other day I was exploring the Nexus and not just running to the usual points. I saw a caved in tunnel, two NPC's, one was a dwarf just staring blankly into the rubble - it was hilarious. Talk to him and the NPC says not to bother the dwarf he is depressed that his brother is now trapped in a cave in.  Hail the dwarf and he calls for his brother saying soon he will dig him out. You will NEVER see that much detail in DAOC. Down to the very last drop of content. <br>
<br>
In the time it takes to get to 1000 in a skill system in DAOC, I could have probably camped Ragefire, AC, and any other notorious camp out there and gotten my items.  <br>
<br>
The biggest point? How about the memories which <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> make</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> an MMORPG? Some of my best memories are of camping those items. Helping others and getting to see their happiness when they get something they have wanted. One of my biggest memories was of the ragefire camp and he didn't even spawn. Sure, it sucked we were all their for 96 hours straight. But man, I was taking pager and cell phone numbers left and right. People were camping in the corner and sleeping leaving their characters online. I would go to bed and give my number to a person to wake me up if RF spawned. Didn't get RF but the friends we all made that day was amazing - and all for a video game. <br>
<br>
I have a story behind every camped item or item I did not purchase in my inventory on my characters. My necro dagger +8 int in Dalnir where Cabren and I camped that zone for 4 days, ordered pizzas, brought trains, killed ourselves all the time. Than again it sucked that we had to wait so long for the item, but once we got it we were proud of it and it had value to us, even if it was no drop. <br>
<br>
You want me to take a stab at what makes EQ so addicting it could be that. The memories you make in an MMORPG is what makes the MMORPG.  And you're not going to find that in a game where you can go solo a mob and get anything you want. <br>
<br>
RVR is the only memory I have of that game. That and the bitch sessions about boring PvE content. Only RvR memory I have in 3 months of playing was when we had 90 albions attacking the Emain supply keep which the midgards owned. 30 of us defending. All 80-90 of the Albions were huddled in ONE single area - and a cleric went up and pretty much mezzed them all. Was hilarious. I couldn't stop laughing as we slaughtered a force of 80-90 who thought they were safe. <br>
<br>
But you can only have so many of those without any reward system in place. And the time it takes to level in DAOC to get to the meat of the game which is RVR, spending months and months... <br>
<br>
To buy a one time clickable heal. <br>
